Comparative Analysis of Supervised Learning Algorithms¶

1. Objective:¶

The purpose of this project is to explore and complare supervised learning algorithms by applying them to two differnt classidication problems.

2. Problem Statements¶

2.1 Wine Quality Prediction¶

Problem: Given the physicochemical test results of a wine, predict whether the quality is wine is above average.

Why is this problem interesting?
Domain: Predicting the quality of the wine is crucial while determining its price. It is important to correctly identify above-average wines and hence classifiers must lower False Positive rate. It is acceptable if the classifier has a slightly higher False Negative rate. It will be interesting to see how the classifier implements this constraint.
Dataset: The target variable is the multi-class categorical variable and the only couple of classes are dominant. All the independent variables are numerical and there are no missing values in the dataset. Only a few features are slightly skewed. It will be interesting to see whether supervised learning algorithms show any bias/variance on such a clean dataset.

2.2 Income Prediction¶

Problem: Predict whether the income of the individual exceeds 50k a year based on the individual's census data.

Why is this problem interesting?
Domain: Predicting the income of an individual has many practical applications across the financial industry. For example, banks can decide whether to approve a loan based on the predicted income of an individual. In such scenarios, it is crucial to lower False Positive rate and it may be acceptable to have a slightly higher False Negative rate. It will be interesting to see how various classifiers implement these constraints.
Dataset: High-level data exploration revealed that many of the independent features are categorical with many classes and some of these are qualitative while others are quantitative. Few of the features are highly skewed. It will be interesting to see how these features impact the performance of supervised algorithms. I also notice the missing values in some of the instances. I will also be interesting to see whether imputing or removing these instances will create any bias in the model

3. Datasets¶

3.1 Wine Dataset¶

UCI Wine Quality dataset consists physicochemical and sensory data red and white variants of the Portuguese "Vinho Verde" wine. Dataset is available at https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Wine+Quality

Number of Instances: red wine - 1599; white wine - 4898.
Number of Attributes: 11 + output attribute

Attribute Information Input variables (based on physicochemical tests): 1 - fixed acidity 2 - volatile acidity 3 - citric acid 4 - residual sugar 5 - chlorides 6 - free sulfur dioxide 7 - total sulfur dioxide 8 - density 9 - pH 10 - sulphates 11 - alcohol
Output variable (based on sensory data): 12 - quality (score between 0 and 10)

3.1 Census Dataset¶

Dataset was extracted by Barry Becker from the 1994 Census database. A set of reasonably clean records was extracted using the following conditions: ((AAGE>16) && (AGI>100) && (AFNLWGT>1)&& (HRSWK>0)). Dataset is available at https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Census+Income

Number of Instances: 48842
Number of Attributes: 14 + output attribute

Attribute Information: Input Variables: 1 - age 2 - workclass 3- fnlwgt 4 - education 5 - education-num 6 - marital-status 7- occupation 8 - relationship 9 - race 10 - sex 11 - capital-gain 12 - capital-loss 13 - hours-per-week 14 - native-country
Output Variable: 15 - income

#Ploting the class distribution
sns.countplot(x='quality', data = df_combined);

Note that class distribution is not equal and it is instead biased towards 5 and 6. Slight imbalance can be treated like a normal classification predictive modeling problem. Unfortunately in this dataset, we observe Severe imbalance. The classifier will be biased towards the Majority class but it will ignore minority classes such as 4, 8, 9, etc.
Since our goal is to predict whether wine quality above and to get rid of the imbalanced class problem, we will convert this into a binary classification problem. If the quality of the wine is > 5, then the wine is above average If the quality of the wine is <= 5, then the wine is below average.

Class Distribution: Class distribution in both datasets was imbalanced. Wine quality dataset had multiple classes ranging from 3 to 9 but only class 5, 6 and 7 had majority of data. Since our goal is to predict whether wine quality above average, target variable converted to binary. If the quality of the wine is > 5, then the wine is above average (i.e. 1) and if the quality of the wine is <= 5, then the wine is below average (i.e. 0). After this conversion wine quality dataset was still imbalanced. Similarly Census dataset was also imbalanced but none of these two datasets were extremely imbalanced (i.e. 10:1).
Missing Data: Wine dataset was clean without any missing data. Census dataset had missing fields in 3 columns. Rows with missing values were removed because the number of rows were less and imputing categorical variable to mode may introduce bias.
Outliers: Outliers were observed in both datasets which were initially removed using Tukey's method. It was observed that F1 score for all algorithms dropped (3-5%) after removing outliers from the dataset. I learnt that it is not a good practice to just remove the data points because they lie outside the IQR. Only after detailed understanding of domain we can draw possible ranges for each feature variables. These ranges can then be used to remove true outliers. Also tree based algorithms are insensitive to outliers. Hence outliers are not removed for this project due to lack of domain understanding. Finally approach to remove outliers was not implemented for both datasets.
Feature Scaling: For both datasets it was observe that features vary widely in their magnitudes. Features were scaled using StandardScaler to improve the training time of the distance and similarity-based algorithm. Tree-based algorithms are insensitive to feature scaling. Nonetheless we will scale the features of both dataset as it will help in visualizing the data and comparing performance of different algorithms.

5. Modeling and Evaluation Process¶

  1. Split the dataset into Traning and Testing sets.
    Use testing set only of evaluating final model. Use cross valiation for model tuning.
  2. Capture Performance Baseline using Dummy Classifer with Most Frequent Strategy
  3. Repeat this step for KNN, DT, SVM, MLP and ADABoost classifier
    • Capture performance measure for with default hyperparameters
    • Search the hyper-parameter space for the best cross validation score
    • Plot learning curve and carry out bias - variance analysis
    • Carry out hypermeters tuning by ploting validation curves
    • Finalize the model, meaure train and test time and plot ROC curve
  4. Compare the perfromance of all classifiers
In [35]:
size = 10
cv = StratifiedKFold(size, shuffle=True, random_state=1)

#Creating list to capture model statistics
model_stats = []

Performance Measure: As classes in both datasets are imbalanced, I did not use Accuracy as performance metric. TPR and FPR are important in both problems hence F1 score will be most suitable to measure the performance of model. Learning curves were analyzed by plotting F1 score against the number of iterations. Learning curve provided insights on whether model tuning is effective and provided details on bias and variance of model.
As mentioned in the problem statement earlier, focus is more on the positive classes than on the negative classes and we want to choose the threshold that fits our business problem. Hence, I used Precision Recall curve because ROC AUC focuses mainly on the positive class (PPV and TPR) and it cares less about the frequent negative class. PR curve is also selected because both datasets has imbalanced classes.

Cross Validation: I used stratified K-Fold cross validation to balance the classes in both datasets. Stratified K-Fold cross validation balances positive and negative classes for each fold. It ensured majority class is not overrepresented in the training dataset. Size of K was chosen as 10 based on the empirical data available on experimental machine learning. Since classes were not extremely imbalanced and supervised algorithms performed satisfactorily and hence, I avoided implementation of SMOTE algorithm.

Acceptable Score: To determine the acceptable value of F1 score we need domain understand. I do not have deep understanding of the feature in both datasets. Looking at the performance of the dummy classifiers I determine acceptable score of 0.75 for both datasets

6.2.3 Observations¶

Classifier with default sklearn parameters: For both datasets KNN classifier with default parameters performed better than Dummy classifier.
Wine dataset: High training score and large gap between training and cross-validation scores indicates that model has high variance and low bias.
Census dataset: Low cv score and large gap between training and cross-validation scores indicates that model has high variance and high bias.
Hyperparameter Tuning – Iteration 1: Optimal value of parameters n_neighbors and leaf_size was searched using GridSearchCV. For wine dataset, optimal value of neighbors was 56 and for leaf_size was 1. Learning curves were plotted using these parameters and it was observed that these parameters brought the train and cv curves much closer. There was not drastic change in the F1 score.
For census dataset, optimal value of neighbors was 36 and for leaf_size was 21. Learning curves were plotted using these parameters and it was observed that these parameters brought the train and cv curves much closer. There 5 point increase in Precision but was not change in the F1 score.
Hyperparameter Tuning – Iteration 2: Validation curves were plotted for both datasets to identify optimum values of ‘distance’ and ‘metric’ hyperparameters. For both dataset best value for weights was distance and best value for metric was Manhattan. When learning curves were plotted using these optimum values both of models showed slight improvement in cv scores but both models were overfitting the training data. One possible reason for this observation is that the input variables are similar in type. Hence these hyper parameters were dropped, and I ran multiple iterations to find the optimal n_neighbours parameter.
Wine dataset: n_neighbors=117
Census dataset: n_neighbors=13
Learning curves plotted optimal n_neighbors identified in previous step.
Wine dataset: Both training and cv curves merge above the expected score is a good indicator of well performing model.
Census dataset: Training and cv curves do not merge and bias and variance exists. Both curves are trending upwards because increase in the training samples size provides more neighbors which leads to better accuracy.
Following causes which may result in bias and variance in Census dataset were ruled out –

  • Biased split of train and cv dataset is not possible due to use of stratified Kfold sampling.
  • Sensitivity to noisy or irrelevant attributes is not possible because features are scaled.

Performance of Test Set: Wine Dataset: Performance of tuned model on the held-out test dataset was up to the expected value. F1 score on test data was 0.81 and Average Precision for PR curve was 0.88.
Census Dataset: Performance of tuned model on the held-out test dataset was around the expected value. F1 score on test data was 0.68 and Average Precision for PR curve was 0.72.
Based on the PR curves we can conclude that both models have generalized well.

# This method of copied from Scikit-Learn exmpales available at 
# https://scikit-learn.org/stable/auto_examples/tree/plot_cost_complexity_pruning.html
def plot_cost_complexity_pruning(model, X, Y):
    
    X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, random_state=1, test_size=0.20)
    model.fit(X_train, Y_train)
    print("Train-F1:",round(np.mean(cross_val_score(model,X_train,Y_train,scoring='f1_macro')),2))
    print("Test-F1:",round(f1_score(Y_test,model.predict(X_test),average='macro'),2))
    print(classification_report(Y_train,model.predict(X_train)))
    print(classification_report(Y_test,model.predict(X_test)))
    path=model.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train,Y_train)
    ccp_alphas,impurities=path.ccp_alphas,path.impurities
    print(ccp_alphas)
    print(impurities)
    clfs=[]
    for ccp_alpha in ccp_alphas:
        clf=DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1,ccp_alpha=ccp_alpha,class_weight='balanced')
        clf=clf.fit(X_train,Y_train);
        clfs.append(clf)
    clfs=clfs[:-1]
    ccp_alphas=ccp_alphas[:-1]
    train_scores=[f1_score(Y_train,clf.predict(X_train),average='binary') for clf in clfs]
    test_scores=[f1_score(Y_test,clf.predict(X_test),average='binary') for clf in clfs]
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    ax.set_xlabel("alpha")
    ax.set_ylabel("F1 score")
    ax.set_title("F1 score vs alpha for training and cv sets")
    ax.plot(ccp_alphas, train_scores, marker='o', label="train",
            drawstyle="steps-post")
    ax.plot(ccp_alphas, test_scores, marker='o', label="test",
            drawstyle="steps-post")
    ax.legend()
    plt.show()

6.3.3 Observations¶

Classifier with default sklearn parameters: Decision Tree classifiers with default parameters performed better than Dummy classifier on both datasets. Learning curve for both datasets shows that classifier is overfitting. High training score and large gap between training and cross-validation scores indicates that model has high variance and low bias. Classifiers with default parameters has created complex decision tree because of which model overfits and leads to low bias and high variance. To fix this issue of high variance, optimal splitting criteria will be determined in first iteration.
Hyperparameter Tuning – Iteration 1: For wine datasets, optimal split criteria of information gain (entropy) was selected using GridSearchCV. Performance of both datasets has not improved much using this hyperparameter. Both models still overfits with high variance. F1 score was slightly increased by 0.01. (For learning curves please refer associated notebook).
Entropy uses log calculations and hence slightly more computationally expensive than Gini Index. But the way both techniques measure impurity is similar and hence I did not see change in the classifier’s performance.
Hyperparameter Tuning – Iteration 2 (Post Pruning): To eliminate the overfitting and reduce the misclassification, I carried out post pruning of a decision trees with cost complexity pruning. Pre-pruning deal with noise during learning process whereas post-pruning methods deals with noise already learnt by the model.
For wine dataset ccp alpha of 0.007 gave the highest accuracy, whereas for census dataset the value was 0.002. In this iteration validation curves were plotted for some other parameters (such as splitter) to assess their impact on model’s performance. It was observed that these parameters do not have any significant impact hence those were not included in next step. For validation curves refer associated notebook for validation curves.
Learning curves plotted for iteration 2 shows that for Wine datasets training and cv curves merge. There is no significant change in the F1 score, but True Positive has increased, and False Positive also increased which lead to drop in precision.
For Census dataset also training and cv curves merge. F1 score increased. True Positive has slightly reduced and False Positive drastically reduced which lead to high precision.
Performance of Test Set: Wine Dataset: Performance of tuned model on the held-out test dataset was up to the expected value. F1 score on test data was 0.80 and Average Precision for PR curve was 0.84.
Census Dataset: Performance of tuned model on the held-out test dataset was around the expected value. F1 score on test data was 0.69 and Average Precision for PR curve was 0.76. Although F1 score is less, model has high precision which leads to lower false positive rate.

6.4.3 Observations¶

Classifier with default sklearn parameters: SVC classifier with default parameters performed better than Dummy classifier. For wine dataset, learning curve show training & cv score and small gap between training and cv curves which indicates that model has low variance and low bias. For census dataset, gap between training and cv curves is also small but training and cv scores are also low which indicates significant bias and variance in the classifier.
Hyperparameter Tuning – Iteration 1: During this iteration, optimal values of C and gamma was identified by using GridSearchCV. For both wine dataset and census dataset, optimal value of C was 10 and gamma was 0.1. Learning curves were plotted using these parameters and it was observed that score for both datasets was marginally improved.
C which is a cost of misclassification impact bias and variance. Larger the C leads to lower bias and higher variance because it penalizes the cost of misclassification by large factor. Gamma controls the shape of the peaks where you raise the points. Smaller gamma leads to pointed bump in the higher dimensions which leads to lower bias and higher variance.
Hyperparameter Tuning – Iteration 2: Validation curves were plotted for both datasets to identify best kernel method. Note that rbf has highest error in both datasets. Next best performing kernel function was poly. Some of these kernel functions were plotted using learning curves to capture classifier’s performance.
In this step, ‘rbf’ kernel method was used on both datasets. Precision of both classifiers has slightly improved. Training and cv curves for both datasets still has gap. Wine classifier has maintained high accuracy on the cv set.
Low accuracy score for Census dataset continues the same. TP for both datasets decreased while FP for Census dataset increased substantially. Hence we can conclude that ‘rbf’ kernel function is not suitable for these datasets.
In this step, ‘linear’ kernel method was used for wine dataset whereas ‘poly’ kernel method was used for Census datasets. Notice that training and cv curves merge for wine dataset whereas training and cv curves are very close to merging. Wine classifier has low variance and low bias whereas Income classifier has low variance but higher bias.
Performance of Test Set: Wine Dataset: Performance of tuned model on the held-out test dataset was up to the expected value. F1 score on test data was 0.81 and Average Precision for PR curve was 0.86.
Census Dataset: Performance of tuned model on the held-out test dataset was around the expected value. F1 score on test data was 0.71 and Average Precision for PR curve was 0.76. Based on the PR curves we can conclude that both models have generalized well.

Classifier with default sklearn parameters: MLP classifier with default parameters performed better than Dummy classifier. For wine dataset, learning curve show high training & cv score and small gap between training and cv curves which indicates that model has low variance and low bias. For census dataset, gap between training and cv curves is also small but training and cv scores are also low which indicates significant reasonable bias and low variance in the classifier.
Hyperparameter Tuning – Iteration 1: In this iteration optimal values of hidden units and learning rates were searched using GridSearchCV. For wine dataset, optimal value for hidden layers was 70 and learning rate was 0.002 whereas these parameters for census dataset was 150 and 0.0025 respectively. Performance of both datasets has not improved much using these hyperparameters. Classifier for wine dataset still has low variance and low bias. Classifier for census dataset shows low variance and high bias.
Hyperparameter Tuning – Iteration 2: As activation function is crucial to represent non-linear complex functions, instep step I carried out model complexity on activation function for both datasets.
As both of our problem are binary classification problems, logistics activation function is expected to give better results which is also evident from the validation curves plotted for each of the datasets.
Learning curves plotted during this iteration shows that for wine dataset training and cv curves merge. But F1 score was dropped by 2 points as compare to iteration 1. One reason for early overlap may be that there is a little variance in the combination of feature values and labels. For census dataset, there isn’t much change in the learning curves. Bias and variance exist in the classifier.
Performance of Test Set: Wine Dataset: Performance of tuned model on the held out test dataset was up to the expected value. F1 score on test data was 0.83 and Average Precision for PR curve was 0.89.
Census Dataset: Performance of tuned model on the held-out test dataset was around the expected value. F1 score on test data was 0.70 and Average Precision for PR curve was 0.78.
Based on the PR curves we can conclude that both models have generalized well.

Classifier with default sklearn parameters: AdaBoost classifier with default parameters performed better than Dummy classifier. Learning curve for wine quality shows that classifier is overfitting. High training score and large gap between training and cross-validation scores indicates that model has high variance and low bias.
Learning curve for Census dataset indicates large gap is training and cv curves and low cv score. We can conclude that classifier has high bias as well as high variance.
Hyperparameter Tuning – Iteration 1: In this iteration I aggressively pruned the decision tree algorithms which made these base estimators a weak learner with high bias and low variance. AdaBoost classifier combines these week learners and resulted in low variance and low bias. Low bias is achieved because error in the previous model is reduced by subsequent model. Low variance is achieved as classifier is constraint to individual constraints of each weak learner. Thus, combining simpler models has higher chance of getting a robust model (no overfitting), than combining very complex models.
Wine Dataset: With weak learners’ classifier was not overfitting. Also, both training and cv curves merged at accuracy above expected value indicating that classifier has low bias and low variance.
Census Dataset: Performance of the classifier with weak learner improved drastically. There was substantial increase in TP instances and FP instances also decreased substantially.
Hyperparameter Tuning – Iteration 2: In this iteration model complexity analysis was performed on both datasets for 'algorithm' parameter. F1 score was calculated for two values of algorithm parameters viz. 'SAMME', 'SAMME.R'. In bot of the datasets it was observed the 'SAMME.R' performed better. The SAMME.R algorithm typically converges faster than SAMME, achieving a lower test error with fewer boosting iterations. I have not noticed any substantial performance difference between then when I plotted learning curve using 'SAMME.R'. I could not identify any explanation for this behavior.
Performance of Test Set: Wine Dataset: Performance of tuned model on the held out test dataset was up to the expected value. F1 score on test data was 0.81 and Average Precision for PR curve was 0.83.
Census Dataset: Performance of tuned model on the held-out test dataset was lower than expected value. F1 score on test data was 0.61 and Average Precision for PR curve was 0.80.
Based on the PR curves we can conclude that both models have generalized well. Notice that for Census dataset, F1 score is just 0.57 whereas AP (also known as PRAUC) is 80. This is because AUCPR includes integration over the entire range of precision and recall tradeoffs, while the F1 score takes one specific instance of precision and recall pair.

Training and testing time depend on the size and complexity of the data. Census dataset is 5 times larger than Wine quality dataset. You can see that training time for Census dataset is much higher as compared to Wine Quality dataset. Same is not true with the test time.
For wine dataset, KNN algorithm took least amount of time to train the model whereas SVC took the greatest amount of time to train the model. SVC also took highest amount of time to train the model on Census dataset. Decision tree was fastest to train the model on Census dataset. SVC also has high test time on both datasets.
One possible explanation is that the time taken by SVC to train is proportional to the third power of the number of training samples and prediction time is polynomial in terms of number of test vectors.
MLP was the fastest to predict on Wine Quality dataset. Decision Tree was fastest to predict on Census datasets. Decision tree was also close to MLP on Wine Quality dataset.

Wine Dataset:
All classifier performed better than the dummy classifier and achieved score more than target of 0.80. MLP and KNN classifiers were the two best performing algorithms on the Wine Quality dataset. Whereas AdaBoost and Decision Tree algorithms performed least. Decision Tree performed the least most likely because presence of un-correlated variables. Also, as DT implements greedy strategy to find the right starting point of the tree which greatly impacts the result because small changes early on can have big impacts later.

Overall MLP is the most suitable algorithm for wine classification problem.

Census Dataset: All classifier performed better than the dummy classifier and achieved score more than target of 0.7. Adaboost and MLP classifiers were the two best performing algorithms on the Census dataset. Whereas KNN and Decision Tree algorithms performed least.

Overall AdaBoost is the most suitable algorithm for income classification problem. As we have seen that during dataset analysis, Census dataset has very few features which are highly correlated with income. AdaBoost training process selects only those features known to improve the predictive power of the model, reducing dimensionality and potentially improving execution time as irrelevant features need not be computed.
As we can see Decision tree classifier has not performed well as compared to AdaBoost because they are extremely sensitive to small changes in the data and a slight change can result in a drastically different tree. DT can easily overfit which was taken care in AdaBoost by aggressive pruning.
